<font color="#FF0000">REMEMBRANCE</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jan  6 22:59:09 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I wasn't there, and as a Persian Gulf vet I came home to quite a different reception...  But my dad was there..<br>
3rd Force Recon, USMC.  I remember my mom telling me as a child not to talk about what daddy did. (And if we did, NEVER to tell what kind of unit he was in.)  I remember my dad coming home and crying every night for the first few months, and his blank stare.  And the cold stares of the people in the community when he did venture outside.  (And, yes, he and the servicemen with him WERE spit on and boo'd when we met him at San Fransico Airport when he returned)<br><br>
I think one thing the protesters didn't realize back then was that the servicemen were also the VICTIMS of the war, not the propagators of it.<br><br>
I cried recently when I read the book &quot;The Wall&quot;, about the Viet Nam Memorial..  I was stationed in Washington D.C. for 6 years and never got quite the emotional impact that I got from one picture in the book.  It's a man in his jungle fatigues holding a sign:  <br>
 <br>
&quot;I like the wall.. and if it makes it harder for them to send us to war, then I like it even more&quot;  (paraphrased)<br>

